'''Myung Film Co., Ltd.''' ([[Hangul]]: 명필름) is a [[South Korea]]n [[film industry|film]] production and distribution company. Established in the [[South Korea|Republic of Korea]] by [[Shim Jae-myung]], the company has distributed films throughout [[South Korea]] since its founding in September 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economy.hankooki.com/lpage/industry/201310/e20131028175459120180.htm|title=심재명 명필름 대표, "리더는 공감 능력이 가장 중요"|accessdate=28 April 2014|date=28 October 2013|work=서울경제|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Myung Films|url=https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/films/index/company.jsp?companyCd=20100545|website=[[Korean Film Council]]|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In 2015, film critics credit Myung Films for its contribution to enhance the development and industrialization of the Korean film industry since its inception.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chung|first1=Joo-won|title=Myung Films fuels Korean movie industry|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20150326000942|website=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=1 July 2018|date=26 March 2015}}</ref>

On 30 April 2015, it opened Myung Films Art Center and Myung Films Institute at the Myung Films HQ building in Paju City of Gyeonggi Province. The Art Center comprises a movie theater, an art performance stage and an art project exhibition hall.<ref>{{cite web|title=MyunMyung Films Institute welcomes talented students for movie making|url=http://english.donga.com/List/3/all/26/410612/1|website=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|accessdate=1 July 2018|date=2 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Myung Films Paju Building / IROJE Architects & Planners|url=https://www.archdaily.com/772573/myung-films-paju-building-iroje-architects-and-planners|website=[[ArchDaily]]|accessdate=1 July 2018|date=2 September 2015}}</ref>

The Myung Films Institute offers a two-year program which comprises courses for various movie theories, liberal arts education, and production practice. 10 students are recruited each year in areas of (a) Drama movie directing (2 students), (b) Documentary directing (1 student), (c) Production (1 student), (d) Acting (2 students) and (e) Cinema art - Filming, Editing and Sound (1 student each). The institute provides all expenses for movie-making, tuition and dormitory accommodation for its students.

The institute's first feature film ''[[In Between Seasons]]'' (2016) was directed by first-time director [[Lee Dong-eun]] who graduated from its first Film Directing major graduating class. ''In Between Seasons'' was screened in the New Currents section at the [[21st Busan International Film Festival]] where it won the KNN Award. Lee went on to make his second feature, the critically acclaimed ''[[Mothers (2017 South Korean film)|Mothers]]'' (2017) which won the NETPAC Award at the 2018 [[Vesoul International Film Festival of Asian Cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Christopher|last=Weatherspoon|title=In Between Seasons|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/newfilm.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601011&seq=301&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=In+Between+Seasons|website=[[Korean Film Council]]|accessdate=1 July 2018|date=20 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Pierce|last=Conran|title=LEE Dong-eun's Sophomore Drama with LIM Soo-jung Awarded in France|url=https://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?blbdComCd=601006&seq=4706&mode=VIEW|website=[[Korean Film Council]]|accessdate=2 July 2018|date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

